# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adnaviria
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adnaviria/a-dna] Like the more common B-DNA, A-DNA is a right-handed double helix with major and minor grooves.
[src:adnaviria/a-dna] However, as shown in the comparison table below, there is a slight increase in the number of base pairs (bp) per turn.
[src:adnaviria/a-dna] This results in a smaller twist angle, and smaller rise per base pair, so that A-DNA is 20-25% shorter than B-DNA.
[src:adnaviria/a-dna] The major groove of A-DNA is deep and narrow, while the minor groove is wide and shallow.
[src:adnaviria/a-dna] A-DNA is broader and more compressed along its axis than B-DNA.
[src:adnaviria/a-dna] The identifiable characteristic of A-DNA X-ray crystallography is the hole in the center.
[src:adnaviria/a-dna] A-DNA has a C3'-endo pucker, which refers to the C3' carbon in the furanose ring being below the sugar plane.
[src:adnaviria/a-dna] Research also indicates that A-form DNA can hybridize with the more common B-DNA.
[src:adnaviria/a-dna] These A–B intermediate forms adopt the sugar pucker properties and/or the base conformation of both DNA forms.
[src:adnaviria/a-dna] In one study, the characteristic C3'-endo pucker is found on the first three sugars of the DNA strand, while the last three sugars have a C2'-endo pucker, like B-DNA.
[src:adnaviria/a-dna] These intermediates can form in aqueous solutions when the cytosine bases are methylated or brominated, altering the conformation.
[src:adnaviria/a-dna] Alternatively, guanine and cytosine rich fragments have been shown to be easily converted from B to A-form in aqueous solutions.
[src:adnaviria/a-dna] A-DNA can be derived from a few processes, including dehydration and protein binding.
[src:adnaviria/a-dna] Dehydration of DNA drives it into the A form, which has been shown to protect DNA under conditions such as the extreme desiccation of bacteria.
[src:adnaviria/a-dna] Protein binding can also strip solvent off of DNA and convert it to the A form, as revealed by the structure of several hyperthermophilic archaeal viruses.
[src:adnaviria/a-dna] These viruses include rod-shaped rudiviruses SIRV2 and SSRV1, enveloped filamentous lipothrixviruses AFV1, SFV1 and SIFV, tristromavirus PFV2 as well as icosahedral portoglobovirus SPV1.
[src:adnaviria/a-dna] A-form DNA is believed to be one of the adaptations of hyperthermophilic archaeal viruses to harsh environmental conditions in which these viruses thrive.
[src:adnaviria/a-dna] It has been proposed that the motors that package double-stranded DNA in bacteriophages exploit the fact that A-DNA is shorter than B-DNA, and that conformational changes in the DNA itself are the source of the large forces generated by these motors.
[src:adnaviria/a-dna] Experimental evidence for A-DNA as an intermediate in viral biomotor packing comes from double dye Förster resonance energy transfer measurements showing that B-DNA is shortened by 24% in a stalled ("crunched") A-form intermediate.
[src:adnaviria/a-dna] In this model, ATP hydrolysis is used to drive protein conformational changes that alternatively dehydrate and rehydrate the DNA, and the DNA shortening/lengthening cycle is coupled to a protein-DNA grip/release cycle to generate the forward motion that moves DNA into the capsid.
[src:adnaviria/acidianus-filamentous-virus-1] Viruses in *Captovirus* are enveloped, with rod-shaped geometries.
[src:adnaviria/acidianus-filamentous-virus-1] The diameter is around 24 nm, with a length of 900 nm.
[src:adnaviria/acidianus-filamentous-virus-1] Genomes are linear, around 20kb in length.
[src:adnaviria/acidianus-filamentous-virus-1] Entry into the host cell is achieved by adsorption into the host cell.
[src:adnaviria/acidianus-filamentous-virus-1] DNA-templated transcription is the method of transcription.
[src:adnaviria/acidianus-filamentous-virus-1] Archaea acidianus serve as the natural host.
[src:adnaviria/acidianus-filamentous-virus-1] Transmission routes are passive diffusion.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] The extracellular particles (virions) of adnavirians consist of the genome encased in capsid proteins to form a helical nucleoprotein complex.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] For some of them, this helix is surrounded by a lipid membrane called an envelope.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Some contain an additional protein layer between the nucleoprotein helix and the envelope.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Complete virions are long and thin and may be flexible or stiff like a rod.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] In general, enveloped adnavirians are more flexible than non-enveloped ones.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] At both ends of the virion are protrusions involved in host recognition.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Viruses in the realm use a variety of methods to replicate their genomes and rely on host machinery for transcription.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Virions are assembled and enveloped in the host cell's cytoplasm.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Their A-DNA genome is formed by interactions between pre-genomic B-DNA and the MCP and may be an adaptation to extremely high temperatures.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] They are lytic viruses, leaving their host through ruptures in the cell's external membrane (lysis).
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Adnavirians may have infected the last archaeal common ancestor.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] In general, they have no genetic relation to viruses outside the realm.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] They were first discovered in the 1980s by Wolfram Zillig and his colleagues.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Since its discovery in 1988, the adnavirian Sulfolobus islandicus rod-shaped virus 2 (SIRV2) has become a model for studying virus-host interactions in archaea.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] The realm *Adnaviria* was established in 2021 after cryogenic electron microscopy showed that member viruses shared their A-DNA, MCP, and general virion structure.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Viruses in *Adnaviria* have linear, double-stranded DNA (dsDNA) genomes that range from about 17.6 to 41.5 kilobase pairs in length.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] The ends of their genomes contain inverted terminal repeats.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Their genomes exist in A-form, also called A-DNA, a dehydrated version of the more typical B-form DNA.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] A-DNA has a compact right-handed helix with more base pairs per turn than B-DNA, and the base pairs in A-DNA are not perpendicular to the DNA's helix axis.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] The creation of genomic A-DNA is caused by major capsid protein (MCP) dimers interacting with the phosphodiester bond DNA backbone during virion assembly, covering pre-genomic B-DNA to form a helical nucleoprotein complex that contains genomic A-DNA.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] The A-form genome may be an adaptation to extremely high temperatures.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] The nucleoprotein helix is composed of asymmetric units of two MCPs.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] For rudiviruses, this is a homodimer, a molecule formed by the bonding of two identical MCPs.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] For other adnavirians, it is a heterodimer, a molecule formed by the bonding of two structurally similar MCPs that are paralogous.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] The MCPs of viruses in *Adnaviria* have a folded structure that contains an alpha-helix bundle that has four helices, called the SIRV2 fold, named after Sulfolobus islandicus rod-shaped virus 2 (SIRV2).
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] The four-helix bundle is found at the end (C-terminus) of the protein, while the beginning (N-terminus) of the protein has an extended alpha-helical arm that, when a part of MCP dimers, forms a closed claw-like shape that wraps tightly around the dsDNA genome to change it to A-form.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Variations in the protein structure exist, but the same base structure is retained in all adnavirians.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] The MCP genes are the only core genes found in all viruses in the realm.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] The extracellular bodies (virions) of adnavirians are filamentous, i.e., they are long, thin, and cylindrical.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Virions are about 400–2,000 nanometers (nm) in length and 24–38 nm in diameter.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Lipothrixviruses and ungulaviruses have flexible virions in which the nucleoprotein helix is surrounded by a lipid envelope.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Tristromaviruses likewise have flexible, enveloped virions with an additional protein sheath layer between the nucleoprotein complex and the envelope.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Envelopes are half as thick as the host cell membrane as they are derived from host diether and tetraether lipids that either are short (archaeol) or can be bent into a U shape.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Rudviruses have stiff, non-enveloped, rod-like virions about 600–900 by 23 nm.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Non-enveloped adnavirians are more rigid, while enveloped adnavirians are more flexible.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] At both ends of the virion, lipothrixviruses and ungulaviruses have mop- or claw-like structures connected to a collar, whereas rudiviruses and tristromaviruses have plugs at each end from which bundles of thin filaments emanate.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] These protrusions are usually genus-specific, and they are made of minor structural proteins and involved in host recognition.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Ahmunvirus and chiyouvirus virions have not been studied.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Rudiviruses, tristromaviruses, and ungulaviruses recognize and bind to extracellular filaments during viral entry into the cell.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] For rudiviruses and tristromaviruses, these are type IV pili.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] After reaching the cell surface, rudiviruses virions disassemble, likely at the same time that viral DNA enters the host cell's cytoplasm.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Once there, transcription of viral genes begins, starting with proteins that take over the host and defend against host immune systems, such as anti-CRISPR proteins to protect against CRISPR defense systems.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Adnavirians do not encode their own RNA polymerases, so they rely on host transcription machinery.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] They do, however, encode proteins that regulate transcription.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Most research on adnavirian replication has focused on rudiviruses, but it is known that adnavirians replicate through a variety of mechanisms.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Rudiviruses encode a HUH-superfamily endonuclease, which is thought to initiate rolling circle replication by nicking DNA close to the hairpin at the end of the genome.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] For SIRV2, a rudivirus, replication occurs through a combination of strand-displacement, rolling-circle, and strand-coupled replication, which creates intermediate molecules resembling brushes that contain many copies of the genome.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] These intermediates are then processed into individual genomes.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Acidianus filamentous virus 1, an ungulavirus, appears to start replication first by forming a D-loop, then progressing through a strand-displacement mechanism.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Replication then ends with the help of recombination through the formation of loop-like structures.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Classified adnavirians do not encode their own DNA polymerases, so replication is likely performed by host DNA polymerases.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] For rudiviruses, DNA polymerase B1 and a sliding clamp are involved in replication.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Ahmunviruses encode homologs of the archaeo-eukaryotic primase and DNA polymerase sliding clamp, which likely are important during replication.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Genes for protein-primed family B DNA polymerases have been identified by metagenomics in samples of putative adnavirians, suggesting more replication methods are used by them than what is currently known.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Virions are assembled and enveloped in the cytoplasm.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Characterized adnavirians replicate through the lytic cycle, leaving the cell through ruptures in the cell's external membrane (lysis).
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Rudivirus and lipothrixvirus virions exit the cell through pyramidal structures commonly called virus-associated pyramids (VAPs).
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] VAPs are made of a small virus-encoded protein and are formed at the same time as virions.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] At the end of infection, once VAPs reach a certain size, their triangular surfaces come apart like flower petals.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] This creates openings in the cell envelope through which the contents of the cytoplasm, including virions, pour out of the cell.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Tristromaviruses appear to use a different method of lysis during which cells are sliced open without the formation of surface structures.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Adnavirians are known to infect hyperthermophilic (very high temperature), thermoacidophilic (high temperature, highly acidic), and methanotrophic (methane-metabolizing) archaea.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Known and predicted hosts include thermophilic archaea of the orders Sulfolobales (rudiviruses, lipothrixviruses, ungulaviruses), Thermoproteales (tristromaviruses), and *Candidatus* Bathyarchaeales (chiyouviruses), all of which belong to the phylum Thermoproteota.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Ahmunviruses infect anaerobic methanotrophic archaea of the class *Candidatus* Syntropharchaeia in the phylum Halobacteriota.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Adnavirians can be found worldwide, though some, such as rudiviruses, are concentrated in extreme geothermal environments.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Adnavirians have potentially existed for a long time, as it is thought that they may have infected the last archaeal common ancestor.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] In general, they show no genetic relation to viruses outside the realm.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Adnavirian genes found in viruses outside the realm include those that encode glycosyltransferases, ribbon-helix-helix transcription factors, and anti-CRISPR proteins.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Adnavirians are morphologically similar to non-archaeal filamentous viruses, but their virions are built from different capsid proteins.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Viruses of *Clavaviridae*, a family of filamentous archaeal viruses, likewise possess MCPs and virion organization that are unrelated to the MCPs and virion organization of viruses in *Adnaviria* and for that reason are excluded from the realm.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Viruses of *Adnaviria* began to be discovered in the 1980s by Wolfram Zillig and his colleagues.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] To discover these viruses, Zillig developed the methods used to culture their hosts.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] The first of these to be described were TTV1, TTV2, and TTV3 in 1983.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] TTV1 was classified as the first lipothrixvirus but is now classified as a tristromavirus.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] SIRV2, a rudivirus, was discovered in 1988 and has become a model for studying virus-host interactions in archaea.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] The families *Lipothrixviridae* and *Rudiviridae* were then united under the order *Ligamenvirales* in 2013 based on evidence of their relation.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Cryogenic electron microscopy would later show in 2020 that the MCPs of tristromaviruses contained a SIRV2-like fold like ligamenviruses, which provided justification to group them together in the realm *Adnaviria*, created in 2021.
[src:adnaviria/adnaviria] Before the realm was established, *Tokiviricetes*, the name of its only class, was sometimes used to refer to adnavirians.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] An **alpha helix** (or **α-helix**) is a sequence of amino acids in a protein that are twisted into a coil (a helix).
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The alpha helix is the most common structural arrangement in the secondary structure of proteins.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] It is also the most extreme type of local structure, and it is the local structure that is most easily predicted from a sequence of amino acids.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The alpha helix has a right-handed helix conformation in which every backbone N−H group hydrogen bonds to the backbone C=O group of the amino acid that is four residues earlier in the protein sequence.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] is at the bottom and its C-terminus at the top.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Note that the sidechains (black stubs) angle slightly downward, toward the N-terminus, while the peptide oxygens (red) point up and the peptide NHs (blue with grey stubs) point down.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] In the early 1930s, William Astbury showed that there were drastic changes in the X-ray fiber diffraction of moist wool or hair fibers upon significant stretching.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The data suggested that the unstretched fibers had a coiled molecular structure with a characteristic repeat of ≈5.1 ångströms (0.51 nanometres).
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Astbury initially proposed a linked-chain structure for the fibers.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Hans Neurath was the first to show that Astbury's models could not be correct in detail, because they involved clashes of atoms.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Neurath's paper and Astbury's data inspired H.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Taylor, Maurice Huggins and Bragg and collaborators to propose models of keratin that somewhat resemble the modern α-helix.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The pivotal moment came in the early spring of 1948, when Pauling caught a cold and went to bed.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Being bored, he drew a polypeptide chain of roughly correct dimensions on a strip of paper and folded it into a helix, being careful to maintain the planar peptide bonds.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] After a few attempts, he produced a model with physically plausible hydrogen bonds.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Pauling then worked with Corey and Branson to confirm his model before publication.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] In 1954, Pauling was awarded his first Nobel Prize "for his research into the nature of the chemical bond and its application to the elucidation of the structure of complex substances" (such as proteins), prominently including the structure of the α-helix.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The amino acids in an α-helix are arranged in a right-handed helical structure where each amino acid residue corresponds to a 100° turn in the helix (i.e., the helix has 3.6 residues per turn), and a translation of 1.5 Å (0.15 nm) along the helical axis.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Dunitz describes how Pauling's first article on the theme in fact shows a left-handed helix, the enantiomer of the true structure.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Short pieces of left-handed helix sometimes occur with a large content of achiral glycine amino acids, but are unfavorable for the other normal, biological L-amino acids.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The pitch of the alpha-helix (the vertical distance between consecutive turns of the helix) is 5.4 Å (0.54 nm), which is the product of 1.5 and 3.6.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The most important thing is that the N-H group of one amino acid forms a hydrogen bond with the C=O group of the amino acid *four* residues earlier; this repeated *i* + 4 → *i* hydrogen bonding is the most prominent characteristic of an α-helix.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Official international nomenclature specifies two ways of defining α-helices, rule 6.2 in terms of repeating *φ*, *ψ* torsion angles (see below) and rule 6.3 in terms of the combined pattern of pitch and hydrogen bonding.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The α-helices can be identified in protein structure using several computational methods, such as DSSP (Define Secondary Structure of Protein).
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Similar structures include the 310 helix (*i* + 3 → *i* hydrogen bonding) and the π-helix (*i* + 5 → *i* hydrogen bonding).
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The α-helix can be described as a 3.613 helix, since the *i* + 4 spacing adds three more atoms to the H-bonded loop compared to the tighter 310 helix, and on average, 3.6 amino acids are involved in one ring of α-helix.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The subscripts refer to the number of atoms (including the hydrogen) in the closed loop formed by the hydrogen bond.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Residues in α-helices typically adopt backbone (*φ*, *ψ*) dihedral angles around (−60°, −45°), as shown in the image at right.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] In more general terms, they adopt dihedral angles such that the *ψ* dihedral angle of one residue and the *φ* dihedral angle of the *next* residue sum to roughly −105°.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] As a consequence, α-helical dihedral angles, in general, fall on a diagonal stripe on the Ramachandran diagram (of slope −1), ranging from (−90°, −15°) to (−70°, −35°).
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] For comparison, the sum of the dihedral angles for a 310 helix is roughly −75°, whereas that for the π-helix is roughly −130°.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The α-helix is tightly packed; there is almost no free space within the helix.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The amino-acid side-chains are on the outside of the helix, and point roughly "downward" (i.e., toward the N-terminus), like the branches of an evergreen tree (Christmas tree effect).
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] This directionality is sometimes used in preliminary, low-resolution electron-density maps to determine the direction of the protein backbone.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Helices observed in proteins can range from four to over forty residues long, but a typical helix contains about ten amino acids (about three turns).
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] In general, short polypeptides do not exhibit much α-helical structure in solution, since the entropic cost associated with the folding of the polypeptide chain is not compensated for by a sufficient amount of stabilizing interactions.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] In general, the backbone hydrogen bonds of α-helices are considered slightly weaker than those found in β-sheets, and are readily attacked by the ambient water molecules.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] However, in more hydrophobic environments such as the plasma membrane, or in the presence of co-solvents such as trifluoroethanol (TFE), or isolated from solvent in the gas phase, oligopeptides readily adopt stable α-helical structure.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Furthermore, crosslinks can be incorporated into peptides to conformationally stabilize helical folds.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Crosslinks stabilize the helical state by entropically destabilizing the unfolded state and by removing enthalpically stabilized "decoy" folds that compete with the fully helical state.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] It has been shown that α-helices are more stable, robust to mutations and designable than β-strands in natural proteins, and also in artificially designed proteins.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The three most popular ways of visualizing the alpha-helical secondary structure of oligopeptide sequences are (1) a helical wheel, (2) a wenxiang diagram, and (3) a helical net.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Each of these can be visualized with various software packages and web servers.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] To generate a small number of diagrams, Heliquest can be used for helical wheels, and NetWheels can be used for helical wheels and helical nets.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] To programmatically generate a large number of diagrams, helixvis can be used to draw helical wheels and wenxiang diagrams in the R and Python programming languages.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Since the α-helix is defined by its hydrogen bonds and backbone conformation, the most detailed experimental evidence for α-helical structure comes from atomic-resolution X-ray crystallography such as the example shown at right.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] It is clear that all the backbone carbonyl oxygens point downward (toward the C-terminus) but splay out slightly, and the H-bonds are approximately parallel to the helix axis.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Protein structures from NMR spectroscopy also show helices well, with characteristic observations of nuclear Overhauser effect (NOE) couplings between atoms on adjacent helical turns.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] In some cases, the individual hydrogen bonds can be observed directly as a small scalar coupling in NMR.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] There are several lower-resolution methods for assigning general helical structure.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The NMR chemical shifts (in particular of the Cα, Cβ and C′) and residual dipolar couplings are often characteristic of helices.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The far-UV (170–250 nm) circular dichroism spectrum of helices is also idiosyncratic, exhibiting a pronounced double minimum at around 208 and 222 nm.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Infrared spectroscopy is rarely used, since the α-helical spectrum resembles that of a random coil (although these might be discerned by, e.g., hydrogen-deuterium exchange).
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Finally, cryo electron microscopy is now capable of discerning individual α-helices within a protein, although their assignment to residues is still an active area of research.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Long homopolymers of amino acids often form helices if soluble.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Such long, isolated helices can also be detected by other methods, such as dielectric relaxation, flow birefringence, and measurements of the diffusion constant.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] In stricter terms, these methods detect only the characteristic prolate (long cigar-like) hydrodynamic shape of a helix, or its large dipole moment.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Different amino-acid sequences have different propensities for forming α-helical structure.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Alanine, uncharged glutamate, leucine, charged arginine, methionine and charged lysine have especially high helix-forming propensities, whereas proline and glycine have poor helix-forming propensities.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Proline either breaks or kinks a helix, both because it cannot donate an amide hydrogen bond (because it has none) and because its sidechain interferes sterically with the backbone of the preceding turn – inside a helix, which forces a bend of about 30° in the helix's axis.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] However, proline is often the *first* residue of a helix, presumably due to its structural rigidity.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] At the other extreme, glycine also tends to disrupt helices because its high conformational flexibility makes it entropically expensive to adopt the relatively constrained α-helical structure.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Estimated differences in free energy change, Δ(Δ*G*), estimated in kcal/mol per residue in an α-helical configuration, relative to alanine arbitrarily set as zero.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Higher numbers (more positive free energy changes) are less favoured.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Significant deviations from these average numbers are possible, depending on the identities of the neighbouring residues.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] A helix has an overall dipole moment due to the aggregate effect of the individual microdipoles from the carbonyl groups of the peptide bond pointing along the helix axis.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The effects of this macrodipole are a matter of some controversy. α-helices often occur with the N-terminal end bound by a negatively charged group, sometimes an amino acid side chain such as glutamate or aspartate, or sometimes a phosphate ion.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Some regard the helix macrodipole as interacting electrostatically with such groups.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Others feel that this is misleading and it is more realistic to say that the hydrogen bond potential of the free NH groups at the N-terminus of an α-helix can be satisfied by hydrogen bonding; this can also be regarded as set of interactions between local microdipoles such as C=O···H−N.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Coiled-coil α helices are highly stable forms in which two or more helices wrap around each other in a "supercoil" structure.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Coiled coils contain a highly characteristic sequence motif known as a **heptad repeat**, in which the motif repeats itself every seven residues along the sequence (*amino acid* residues, not DNA base-pairs).
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The first and especially the fourth residues (known as the *a* and *d* positions) are almost always hydrophobic; the fourth residue is typically leucine – this gives rise to the name of the structural motif called a *leucine zipper*, which is a type of coiled-coil.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] These hydrophobic residues pack together in the interior of the helix bundle.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] In general, the fifth and seventh residues (the *e* and *g* positions) have opposing charges and form a salt bridge stabilized by electrostatic interactions.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Fibrous proteins such as keratin or the "stalks" of myosin or kinesin often adopt coiled-coil structures, as do several dimerizing proteins.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] A pair of coiled-coils – a four-helix bundle – is a very common structural motif in proteins.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] For example, it occurs in human growth hormone and several varieties of cytochrome.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The Rop protein, which promotes plasmid replication in bacteria, is an interesting case in which a single polypeptide forms a coiled-coil and two monomers assemble to form a four-helix bundle.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The amino acids that make up a particular helix can be plotted on a helical wheel, a representation that illustrates the orientations of the constituent amino acids (see the article for leucine zipper for such a diagram).
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Changes in binding orientation also occur for facially-organized oligopeptides.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] This pattern is especially common in antimicrobial peptides, and many models have been devised to describe how this relates to their function.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Common to many of them is that the hydrophobic face of the antimicrobial peptide forms pores in the plasma membrane after associating with the fatty chains at the membrane core.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Myoglobin and hemoglobin, the first two proteins whose structures were solved by X-ray crystallography, have very similar folds made up of about 70% α-helix, with the rest being non-repetitive regions, or "loops" that connect the helices.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] In classifying proteins by their dominant fold, the Structural Classification of Proteins database maintains a large category specifically for all-α proteins.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Hemoglobin then has an even larger-scale quaternary structure, in which the functional oxygen-binding molecule is made up of four subunits.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] α-Helices have particular significance in DNA binding motifs, including helix-turn-helix motifs, leucine zipper motifs and zinc finger motifs.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] An example of both aspects is the transcription factor Max (see image at left), which uses a helical coiled coil to dimerize, positioning another pair of helices for interaction in two successive turns of the DNA major groove.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] α-Helices are also the most common protein structure element that crosses biological membranes (transmembrane protein), presumably because the helical structure can satisfy all backbone hydrogen-bonds internally, leaving no polar groups exposed to the membrane if the sidechains are hydrophobic.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Proteins are sometimes anchored by a single membrane-spanning helix, sometimes by a pair, and sometimes by a helix bundle, most classically consisting of seven helices arranged up-and-down in a ring such as for rhodopsins (see image at right) and other G protein–coupled receptors (GPCRs).
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The structural stability between pairs of α-Helical transmembrane domains rely on conserved membrane interhelical packing motifs, for example, the Glycine-xxx-Glycine (or small-xxx-small) motif.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] α-Helices under axial tensile deformation, a characteristic loading condition that appears in many alpha-helix-rich filaments and tissues, results in a characteristic three-phase behavior of stiff-soft-stiff tangent modulus.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Phase I corresponds to the small-deformation regime during which the helix is stretched homogeneously, followed by phase II, in which alpha-helical turns break mediated by the rupture of groups of H-bonds.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Phase III is typically associated with large-deformation covalent bond stretching.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Alpha-helices in proteins may have low-frequency accordion-like motion as observed by the Raman spectroscopy and analyzed via the quasi-continuum model.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Helices not stabilized by tertiary interactions show dynamic behavior, which can be mainly attributed to helix fraying from the ends.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Homopolymers of amino acids (such as polylysine) can adopt α-helical structure at low temperature that is "melted out" at high temperatures.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] This **helix–coil transition** was once thought to be analogous to protein denaturation.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The statistical mechanics of this transition can be modeled using an elegant transfer matrix method, characterized by two parameters: the propensity to initiate a helix and the propensity to extend a helix.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] At least five artists have made explicit reference to the α-helix in their work: Julie Newdoll in painting and Julian Voss-Andreae, Bathsheba Grossman, Byron Rubin, and Mike Tyka in sculpture.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] San Francisco area artist Julie Newdoll, who holds a degree in microbiology with a minor in art, has specialized in paintings inspired by microscopic images and molecules since 1990.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Her painting "Rise of the Alpha Helix" (2003) features human figures arranged in an α helical arrangement.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] According to the artist, "the flowers reflect the various types of sidechains that each amino acid holds out to the world".
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Julian Voss-Andreae is a German-born sculptor with degrees in experimental physics and sculpture.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Since 2001 Voss-Andreae creates "protein sculptures" based on protein structure with the α-helix being one of his preferred objects.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Voss-Andreae has made α-helix sculptures from diverse materials including bamboo and whole trees.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] A monument Voss-Andreae created in 2004 to celebrate the memory of Linus Pauling, the discoverer of the α-helix, is fashioned from a large steel beam rearranged in the structure of the α-helix.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] The 10-foot-tall (3 m), bright-red sculpture stands in front of Pauling's childhood home in Portland, Oregon.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Ribbon diagrams of α-helices are a prominent element in the laser-etched crystal sculptures of protein structures created by artist Bathsheba Grossman, such as those of insulin, hemoglobin, and DNA polymerase.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Byron Rubin is a former protein crystallographer now professional sculptor in metal of proteins, nucleic acids, and drug molecules – many of which featuring α-helices, such as subtilisin, human growth hormone, and phospholipase A2.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Mike Tyka is a computational biochemist at the University of Washington working with David Baker.
[src:adnaviria/alpha-helix] Tyka has been making sculptures of protein molecules since 2010 from copper and steel, including ubiquitin and a potassium channel tetramer.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] These viruses were earlier known as DNA 1 components.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] These viruses are generally found in the Old World.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] A number have been isolated from the New World but their association with their host viruses is still being studied.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] The genome is between 1300 and 1400 nucleotides in length and has three conserved features: a hairpin structure, a single open reading frame (ORF) and an adenine rich region.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] The hairpin structure has a loop that includes the nonanucleotide, TAGTATTAC, which is common to nanoviruses and differs from the TAATATTAC sequence of geminiviruses by one nucleotide.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] In both geminiviruses and nanoviruses this sequence contains the origin of replication (*ori*) and is nicked by the rolling circle replication initiator protein to initiate viral DNA replication.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] On the basis of the hairpin structures alphasatellites can be divided into 5 clades.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] The open reading frame encodes a rolling circle replication initiator protein (Rep) similar to that found in the nanoviruses.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] The encoded protein is about 36.6 kilodalton in molecular weight with about 315 amino acids.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] It is highly conserved with 86.3–100.0% amino acid sequence identity between isolates.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] The adenine rich region is immediately downstream of the *rep* gene and is approximately 153–169 nucleotides in length with an adenine content of between 52.3–58.4%.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] Phylogenectic analysis of this region shows that they can be divided into three clades which correspond to those found on phylogenetic analysis of the entire genome.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] This portion of the genome appears to be redundant.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] A putative second ORF in the genome of an alphasatellite virus has been described.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] The significance of this finding (if any) is not known.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] Recombination occurs between alphasatellites.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] There are no distinctive virions because the viral genomes are encapsidated within the coat protein of the helper virus.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] Alphasatellites associated with the begomoviruses require a begomovirus for movement in plants and insect transmission but are capable of self replication in host plants.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] They do not appear to cause disease in plants or to alter the course of infection by the begomovirus.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] They may be able to reduce the severity of an infection by the begomoviruses.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] Alphasatellites have also been described in association with *Nanoviridae*.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] These tend to be slightly shorter (1100–1300 nucleotides) but to encode proteins in addition to the *rep* gene.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] Because of the multiple component genome of the *Nanoviridae* these were not initially recognised as distinct genomes.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] Alphasatellites may be the target of RNA silencing.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] Alphasatellites are grouped together in the family *Alphasatellitidae*.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] This family has three subfamilies and 20 genera.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] Given the similarities between the *rep* proteins of the alphasatellites and the nanoviruses, it is likely that the alphasatellites evolved from the nanoviruses.
[src:adnaviria/alphasatellitidae] These viruses have been used in the development of viral gene silencing studies.
[src:adnaviria/ampullaviridae] Ampullaviruses have unique morphology, with the virions being bottle-shaped with one narrow end that smoothly expands into a wider end for an overall length of about 230 nm and width of about 75 nm at the broad end.
[src:adnaviria/ampullaviridae] The narrow end projects beyond the viral envelope and is likely used to inject the viral DNA into host cells.
[src:adnaviria/ampullaviridae] The broad end possesses about 20 thin filaments, each that are regularly distributed in a ring.
[src:adnaviria/ampullaviridae] Inside the envelope is a funnel-shaped protein coat that houses the viral DNA.The genome of ampullaviruses is linear, double-stranded DNA that is about 23.8 kilobases in length.
[src:adnaviria/ampullaviridae] The genome contains an estimated 56 or 57 open reading frames that encode for at least six structural proteins.
[src:adnaviria/ampullaviridae] Entry into the host cell is achieved by virus attaching to the host cell.
[src:adnaviria/ampullaviridae] Archaea of the genus *Acidianus* serve as the natural host.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] In aerobic organisms, electrons are shuttled to an electron transport chain, and the final electron acceptor is oxygen.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] Molecular oxygen is an excellent electron acceptor.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] Anaerobes instead use less-oxidizing (in either thermodynamic or kinetics sense) substances such as nitrate (NO− 3), fumarate (C 4H 2O2− 4), sulfate (SO2− 4), or elemental sulfur (S).
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] These terminal electron acceptors have smaller reduction potentials than O2.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] Less energy per oxidized molecule is released.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] Therefore, anaerobic respiration is less efficient than aerobic.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] Anaerobic cellular respiration and fermentation generate ATP in very different ways, and the terms should not be treated as synonyms.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] Cellular respiration (both aerobic and anaerobic) uses highly reduced chemical compounds such as NADH and FADH2 (for example produced during glycolysis and the citric acid cycle) to establish an electrochemical gradient (often a proton gradient) across a membrane.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] This results in an electrical potential or ion concentration difference across the membrane.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] The reduced chemical compounds are oxidized by a series of respiratory integral membrane proteins with sequentially increasing reduction potentials, with the final electron acceptor being oxygen (in aerobic respiration) or another chemical substance (in anaerobic respiration).
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] A proton motive force drives protons down the gradient (across the membrane) through the proton channel of ATP synthase.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] The resulting current drives ATP synthesis from ADP and inorganic phosphate.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] Fermentation, in contrast, does not use an electrochemical gradient but instead uses only substrate-level phosphorylation to produce ATP.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] The electron acceptor NAD+ is regenerated from NADH formed in oxidative steps of the fermentation pathway by the reduction of oxidized compounds.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] These oxidized compounds are often formed during the fermentation pathway itself, but may also be external.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] For example, in homofermentative lactic acid bacteria, NADH formed during the oxidation of glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate is oxidized back to NAD+ by the reduction of pyruvate to lactic acid at a later stage in the pathway.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] In yeast, acetaldehyde is reduced to ethanol to regenerate NAD+.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] There are two important anaerobic microbial methane formation pathways, through carbon dioxide / bicarbonate (HCO− 3) reduction (respiration) or acetate fermentation.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] Anaerobic respiration is a critical component of the global nitrogen, iron, sulfur, and carbon cycles through the reduction of the oxyanions of nitrogen, sulfur, and carbon to more-reduced compounds.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] The biogeochemical cycling of these compounds, which depends upon anaerobic respiration, significantly impacts the carbon cycle and global warming.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] Anaerobic respiration occurs in many environments, including freshwater and marine sediments, soil, subsurface aquifers, deep subsurface environments, and biofilms.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] Even environments that contain oxygen, such as soil, have micro-environments that lack oxygen due to the slow diffusion characteristics of oxygen gas.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] An example of the ecological importance of anaerobic respiration is the use of nitrate as a terminal electron acceptor, or dissimilatory denitrification, which is the main route by which fixed nitrogen is returned to the atmosphere as molecular nitrogen gas.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] The denitrification process is also very important in host-microbe interactions.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] Like mitochondria in oxygen-respiring microorganisms, some single-cellular anaerobic ciliates use denitrifying endosymbionts to gain energy.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] Another example is methanogenesis, a form of carbon-dioxide respiration, that is used to produce methane gas by anaerobic digestion.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] Biogenic methane can be a sustainable alternative to fossil fuels.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] However, uncontrolled methanogenesis in landfill sites releases large amounts of methane into the atmosphere, acting as a potent greenhouse gas.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] Sulfate respiration produces hydrogen sulfide, which is responsible for the characteristic 'rotten egg' smell of coastal wetlands and has the capacity to precipitate heavy metal ions from solution, leading to the deposition of sulfidic metal ores.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] Dissimilatory denitrification is widely used in the removal of nitrate and nitrite from municipal wastewater.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] An excess of nitrate can lead to eutrophication of waterways into which treated water is released.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] Elevated nitrite levels in drinking water can lead to problems due to its toxicity.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] Denitrification converts both compounds into harmless nitrogen gas.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] Specific types of anaerobic respiration are also critical in bioremediation, which uses microorganisms to convert toxic chemicals into less-harmful molecules to clean up contaminated beaches, aquifers, lakes, and oceans.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] For example, toxic arsenate or selenate can be reduced to less toxic compounds by various anaerobic bacteria via anaerobic respiration.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] The reduction of chlorinated chemical pollutants, such as vinyl chloride and carbon tetrachloride, also occurs through anaerobic respiration.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] Anaerobic respiration is useful in generating electricity in microbial fuel cells, which employ bacteria that respire solid electron acceptors (such as oxidized iron) to transfer electrons from reduced compounds to an electrode.
[src:adnaviria/anaerobic-respiration] This process can simultaneously degrade organic carbon waste and generate electricity.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The animal kingdom is divided into five major clades, namely Porifera, Ctenophora, Placozoa, Cnidaria and Bilateria.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The much smaller basal phylum Xenacoelomorpha have an uncertain position within Bilateria.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Animals first appeared in the fossil record in the late Cryogenian period and diversified in the subsequent Ediacaran period in what is known as the Avalon explosion.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Nearly all modern animal phyla first appeared in the fossil record as marine species during the Cambrian explosion, which began around 539 million years ago (Mya), and most classes during the Ordovician radiation 485.4 Mya.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Common to all living animals, 6,331 groups of genes have been identified that may have arisen from a single common ancestor that lived about 650 Mya during the Cryogenian period.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Historically, Aristotle divided animals into those with blood and those without.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical biological classification for animals in 1758 with his *Systema Naturae*, which Jean-Baptiste Lamarck expanded into 14 phyla by 1809.
[src:adnaviria/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into the multicellular **Metazoa** (now synonymous with Animalia) and the Protozoa, single-celled organisms no longer considered animals.
[src:adnaviria/animal] In modern times, the biological classification of animals relies on advanced techniques, such as molecular phylogenetics, which are effective at demonstrating the evolutionary relationships between taxa.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Humans make use of many other animal species for food (including meat, eggs, and dairy products), for materials (such as leather, fur, and wool), as pets and as working animals for transportation, and services.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Dogs, the first domesticated animal, have been used in hunting, in security and in warfare, as have horses, pigeons and birds of prey; while other terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sports, trophies or profits.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Non-human animals are also an important cultural element of human evolution, having appeared in cave arts and totems since the earliest times, and are frequently featured in mythology, religion, arts, literature, heraldry, politics, and sports.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The word *animal* comes from the Latin noun *animal* of the same meaning, which is itself derived from Latin *animalis* 'having breath or soul'.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The biological definition includes all members of the kingdom Animalia.
[src:adnaviria/animal] In colloquial usage, the term *animal* is often used to refer only to nonhuman animals.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The term *metazoa* is derived from Ancient Greek μετα *meta* 'after' (in biology, the prefix *meta-* stands for 'later') and ζῷᾰ *zōia* 'animals', plural of ζῷον *zōion* 'animal'.
[src:adnaviria/animal] A **metazoan** is any member of the group *Metazoa*.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Animals have several characteristics that they share with other living things.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Animals are eukaryotic, multicellular, and aerobic, as are plants and fungi.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Unlike plants and algae, which produce their own food, animals cannot produce their own food, a feature they share with fungi.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Animals ingest organic material and digest it internally.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Typically, there is an internal digestive chamber with either one opening (in Ctenophora, Cnidaria, and flatworms) or two openings (in most bilaterians).
[src:adnaviria/animal] Animal development is controlled by Hox genes, which signal the times and places to develop structures such as body segments and limbs.
[src:adnaviria/animal] During development, the animal extracellular matrix forms a relatively flexible framework upon which cells can move about and be reorganised into specialised tissues and organs, making the formation of complex structures possible, and allowing cells to be differentiated.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The extracellular matrix may be calcified, forming structures such as shells, bones, and spicules.
[src:adnaviria/animal] In contrast, the cells of other multicellular organisms (primarily algae, plants, and fungi) are held in place by cell walls, and so develop by progressive growth.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Nearly all animals make use of some form of sexual reproduction.
[src:adnaviria/animal] They produce haploid gametes by meiosis; the smaller, motile gametes are spermatozoa and the larger, non-motile gametes are ova.
[src:adnaviria/animal] These fuse to form zygotes, which develop via mitosis into a hollow sphere, called a blastula.
[src:adnaviria/animal] In sponges, blastula larvae swim to a new location, attach to the seabed, and develop into a new sponge.
[src:adnaviria/animal] In most other groups, the blastula undergoes more complicated rearrangement.
[src:adnaviria/animal] It first invaginates to form a gastrula with a digestive chamber and two separate germ layers, an external ectoderm and an internal endoderm.
[src:adnaviria/animal] In most cases, a third germ layer, the mesoderm, also develops between them.
[src:adnaviria/animal] These germ layers then differentiate to form tissues and organs.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Repeated instances of mating with a close relative during sexual reproduction generally leads to inbreeding depression within a population due to the increased prevalence of harmful recessive traits.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Animals have evolved numerous mechanisms for avoiding close inbreeding.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Some animals are capable of asexual reproduction, which often results in a genetic clone of the parent.
[src:adnaviria/animal] This may take place through fragmentation; budding, such as in *Hydra* and other cnidarians; or parthenogenesis, where fertile eggs are produced without mating, such as in aphids.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Animals are categorised into ecological groups depending on their trophic levels and how they consume organic material.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Such groupings include carnivores (further divided into subcategories such as piscivores, insectivores, ovivores, etc.), herbivores (subcategorised into folivores, graminivores, frugivores, granivores, nectarivores, algivores, etc.), omnivores, fungivores, scavengers/detritivores, and parasites.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Interactions between animals of each biome form complex food webs within that ecosystem.
[src:adnaviria/animal] In carnivorous or omnivorous species, predation is a consumer–resource interaction where the predator feeds on another organism, its prey, who often evolves anti-predator adaptations to avoid being fed upon.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Selective pressures imposed on one another lead to an evolutionary arms race between predator and prey, resulting in various antagonistic/competitive coevolutions.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Almost all multicellular predators are animals.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Some consumers use multiple methods; for example, in parasitoid wasps, the larvae feed on the hosts' living tissues, killing them in the process, but the adults primarily consume nectar from flowers.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Other animals may have very specific feeding behaviours, such as hawksbill sea turtles which mainly eat sponges.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Most animals rely on biomass and bioenergy produced by plants and phytoplanktons (collectively called producers) through photosynthesis.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Herbivores, as primary consumers, eat the plant material directly to digest and absorb the nutrients, while carnivores and other animals on higher trophic levels indirectly acquire the nutrients by eating the herbivores or other animals that have eaten the herbivores.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Animals oxidise carbohydrates, lipids, proteins and other biomolecules in cellular respiration, which allows the animal to grow and to sustain basal metabolism and fuel other biological processes such as locomotion.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Some benthic animals living close to hydrothermal vents and cold seeps on the dark sea floor consume organic matter produced through chemosynthesis (via oxidising inorganic compounds such as hydrogen sulfide) by archaea and bacteria.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Animals originated in the ocean; all extant animal phyla, except for Micrognathozoa and Onychophora, feature at least some marine species.
[src:adnaviria/animal] However, several lineages of arthropods begun to colonise land around the same time as land plants, between 510 and 471 million years ago, during the Late Cambrian or Early Ordovician periods.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Vertebrates such as the lobe-finned fish *Tiktaalik* started to move on to land in the late Devonian, about 375 million years ago.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Other notable animal groups that colonized land environments are Mollusca, Platyhelmintha, Annelida, Tardigrada, Onychophora, Rotifera, Nematoda.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Animals occupy virtually all of earth's habitats and microhabitats, with faunas adapted to salt water, hydrothermal vents, fresh water, hot springs, swamps, forests, pastures, deserts, air, and the interiors of other organisms.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Animals are however not particularly heat tolerant; very few of them can survive at constant temperatures above 50 °C (122 °F) or in the most extreme cold deserts of continental Antarctica.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The collective global geomorphic influence of animals on the processes shaping the Earth's surface remains largely understudied, with most studies limited to individual species and well-known exemplars.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The blue whale (*Balaenoptera musculus*) is the largest animal that has ever lived, weighing up to 190 tonnes and measuring up to 33.6 metres (110 ft) long.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The largest extant terrestrial animal is the African bush elephant (*Loxodonta africana*), weighing up to 12.25 tonnes and measuring up to 10.67 metres (35.0 ft) long.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The largest terrestrial animals that ever lived were titanosaur sauropod dinosaurs such as *Argentinosaurus*, which may have weighed as much as 73 tonnes, and *Supersaurus* which may have reached 39 metres.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Several animals are microscopic; some Myxozoa (obligate parasites within the Cnidaria) never grow larger than 20 μm, and one of the smallest species (*Myxobolus shekel*) is no more than 8.5 μm when fully grown.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The following table lists estimated numbers of described extant species for the major animal phyla, along with their principal habitats (terrestrial, fresh water, and marine), and free-living or parasitic ways of life.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Species estimates shown here are based on numbers described scientifically; much larger estimates have been calculated based on various means of prediction, and these can vary wildly.
[src:adnaviria/animal] For instance, around 25,000–27,000 species of nematodes have been described, while published estimates of the total number of nematode species include 10,000–20,000; 500,000; 10 million; and 100 million.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Using patterns within the taxonomic hierarchy, the total number of animal species—including those not yet described—was calculated to be about 7.77 million in 2011.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Evidence of animals is found as long ago as the Cryogenian period.
[src:adnaviria/animal] 24-Isopropylcholestane (24-ipc) has been found in rocks from roughly 650 million years ago; it is only produced by sponges and pelagophyte algae.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Its likely origin is from sponges based on molecular clock estimates for the origin of 24-ipc production in both groups.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Analyses of pelagophyte algae consistently recover a Phanerozoic origin, while analyses of sponges recover a Neoproterozoic origin, consistent with the appearance of 24-ipc in the fossil record.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The first body fossils of animals appear in the Ediacaran, represented by forms such as *Charnia* and *Spriggina*.
[src:adnaviria/animal] It had long been doubted whether these fossils truly represented animals, but the discovery of the animal lipid cholesterol in fossils of *Dickinsonia* establishes their nature.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Animals are thought to have originated under low-oxygen conditions, suggesting that they were capable of living entirely by anaerobic respiration, but as they became specialised for aerobic metabolism they became fully dependent on oxygen in their environments.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Many animal phyla first appear in the fossil record during the Cambrian explosion, starting about 539 million years ago, in beds such as the Burgess Shale.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Extant phyla in these rocks include molluscs, brachiopods, onychophorans, tardigrades, arthropods, echinoderms and hemichordates, along with numerous now-extinct forms such as the predatory *Anomalocaris*.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The apparent suddenness of the event may however be an artefact of the fossil record, rather than showing that all these animals appeared simultaneously.
[src:adnaviria/animal] That view is supported by the discovery of *Auroralumina attenboroughii*, the earliest known Ediacaran crown-group cnidarian (557–562 mya, some 20 million years before the Cambrian explosion) from Charnwood Forest, England.
[src:adnaviria/animal] It is thought to be one of the earliest predators, catching small prey with its nematocysts as modern cnidarians do.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Some palaeontologists have suggested that animals appeared much earlier than the Cambrian explosion, possibly as early as 1 billion years ago.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Early fossils that might represent animals appear for example in the 665-million-year-old rocks of the Trezona Formation of South Australia.
[src:adnaviria/animal] These fossils are interpreted as most probably being early sponges.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Trace fossils such as tracks and burrows found in the Tonian period (from 1 gya) may indicate the presence of triploblastic worm-like animals, roughly as large (about 5 mm wide) and complex as earthworms.
[src:adnaviria/animal] However, similar tracks are produced by the giant single-celled protist *Gromia sphaerica*, so the Tonian trace fossils may not indicate early animal evolution.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Around the same time, the layered mats of microorganisms called stromatolites decreased in diversity, perhaps due to grazing by newly evolved animals.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Objects such as sediment-filled tubes that resemble trace fossils of the burrows of wormlike animals have been found in 1.2 gya rocks in North America, in 1.5 gya rocks in Australia and North America, and in 1.7 gya rocks in Australia.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Their interpretation as having an animal origin is disputed, as they might be water-escape or other structures.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Animals are monophyletic, meaning they are derived from a common ancestor.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Animals are the sister group to the choanoflagellates, with which they form the Choanozoa.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Ros-Rocher and colleagues (2021) trace the origins of animals to unicellular ancestors, providing the external phylogeny shown in the cladogram.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Uncertainty of relationships is indicated with dashed lines.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The animal clade had certainly originated by 650 mya, and may have come into being as much as 800 mya, based on molecular clock evidence for different phyla.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The relationships at the base of the animal tree have been debated.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Other than Ctenophora, the Bilateria and Cnidaria are the only groups with symmetry, and other evidence shows they are closely related.
[src:adnaviria/animal] In addition to sponges, Placozoa has no symmetry and was often considered a "missing link" between protists and multicellular animals.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The presence of hox genes in Placozoa shows that they were once more complex.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The Porifera (sponges) have long been assumed to be sister to the rest of the animals, but there is evidence that the Ctenophora may be in that position.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Molecular phylogenetics has supported both the sponge-sister and ctenophore-sister hypotheses.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Sponges are physically very distinct from other animals, and were long thought to have diverged first, representing the oldest animal phylum and forming a sister clade to all other animals.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Despite their morphological dissimilarity with all other animals, genetic evidence suggests sponges may be more closely related to other animals than the comb jellies are.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Sponges lack the complex organisation found in most other animal phyla; their cells are differentiated, but in most cases not organised into distinct tissues, unlike all other animals.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Sponges are almost entirely sessile in their adult stage.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Sponges lack a digestive, circulatory, respiratory, or excretory system.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Instead, they rely on the flow of water through their bodies to perform these functions.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Many have adapted a hollow structure to facilitate the flow of water through their bodies.
[src:adnaviria/animal] They typically feed by drawing in water through pores, filtering out small particles of food.
[src:adnaviria/animal] They absorb oxygen dissolved in water, and they release carbon dioxide and nitrogenous waste into water that flows through them.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Sponges can reproduce sexually and asexually.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Asexual reproduction happens through a variety of mechanisms including by fragmentation, where a piece of the sponge splits off and reestablishes somewhere else.
[src:adnaviria/animal] For sexual reproduction, most sponges are hermaphrodites, they produce both egg and sperm cells.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Comb jellies, members of Ctenophora, are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Ctenophora have distinct tissues, but these are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:adnaviria/animal] They move using large arrays of cilia, called swimming plates.
[src:adnaviria/animal] They have are unique in having colloblasts, structures on their tentacles that help them catch prey.
[src:adnaviria/animal] They have nerve cells, but lack a brain or central nervous system.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Instead their nerves are arranged into a nerve net.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Their nerves are very different from those of other animals, and evidence suggests that their nerves developed independently of the nerves of other animals.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Like Ctenophora, Cnidaria are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:adnaviria/animal] They also have distinct tissues that are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Members of the group Anthozoa, such as sea anemones, coral, and sea pens only are sessile polyps.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Most members of Medusozoa, including jellyfish and most hydrozoans, have a polyp form as well, but also have a motile medusae stage.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The medusae stage are commonly known as jellyfish.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Cnidaria are diploblastic, having only two main germ layers, ectoderm and endoderm.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The tiny placozoans have no permanent digestive chamber and no symmetry; they superficially resemble amoebae.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Their phylogeny is poorly defined, and under active research.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The remaining animals, the great majority—comprising some 29 phyla and over a million species—form the Bilateria clade, which have a bilaterally symmetric body plan.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The Bilateria are triploblastic, with three well-developed germ layers, and their tissues form distinct organs.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The digestive chamber has two openings, a mouth and an anus, and in the Nephrozoa there is an internal body cavity, a coelom or pseudocoelom.
[src:adnaviria/animal] These animals have a head end (anterior) and a tail end (posterior), a back (dorsal) surface and a belly (ventral) surface, and a left and a right side.
[src:adnaviria/animal] A modern consensus phylogenetic tree for the Bilateria is shown below.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Having a front end means that this part of the body encounters stimuli, such as food, favouring cephalisation, the development of a head with sense organs and a mouth.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Many bilaterians have a combination of circular muscles that constrict the body, making it longer, and an opposing set of longitudinal muscles, that shorten the body; these enable soft-bodied animals with a hydrostatic skeleton to move by peristalsis.
[src:adnaviria/animal] They also have a gut that extends through the basically cylindrical body from mouth to anus.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Many bilaterian phyla have primary larvae which swim with cilia and have an apical organ containing sensory cells.
[src:adnaviria/animal] However, over evolutionary time, descendant spaces have evolved which have lost one or more of each of these characteristics.
[src:adnaviria/animal] For example, adult echinoderms are radially symmetric (unlike their larvae), while some parasitic worms have extremely simplified body structures.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Genetic studies have considerably changed zoologists' understanding of the relationships within the Bilateria.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Most appear to belong to two major lineages, the protostomes and the deuterostomes.
[src:adnaviria/animal] It is often suggested that the basalmost bilaterians are the Xenacoelomorpha, with all other bilaterians belonging to the subclade Nephrozoa.
[src:adnaviria/animal] However, this suggestion has been contested, with other studies finding that xenacoelomorphs are more closely related to Ambulacraria than to other bilaterians.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Protostomes and deuterostomes differ in several ways.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Early in development, deuterostome embryos undergo radial cleavage during cell division, while many protostomes (the Spiralia) undergo spiral cleavage.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Animals from both groups possess a complete digestive tract, but in protostomes the first opening of the embryonic gut develops into the mouth, and the anus forms secondarily.
[src:adnaviria/animal] In deuterostomes, the anus forms first while the mouth develops secondarily.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Most protostomes have schizocoelous development, where cells simply fill in the interior of the gastrula to form the mesoderm.
[src:adnaviria/animal] In deuterostomes, the mesoderm forms by enterocoelic pouching, through invagination of the endoderm.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The main deuterostome taxa are the Ambulacraria and the Chordata.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Ambulacraria are exclusively marine and include acorn worms, starfish, sea urchins, and sea cucumbers.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The chordates are dominated by the vertebrates (animals with backbones), which consist of fishes, amphibians, reptiles, birds, and mammals.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The protostomes include the Ecdysozoa, named after their shared trait of ecdysis, growth by moulting, Among the largest ecdysozoan phyla are the arthropods and the nematodes.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The rest of the protostomes are in the Spiralia, named for their pattern of developing by spiral cleavage in the early embryo.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Major spiralian phyla include the annelids and molluscs.
[src:adnaviria/animal] In the classical era, Aristotle divided animals, based on his own observations, into those with blood (roughly, the vertebrates) and those without.
[src:adnaviria/animal] In 1758, Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical classification in his *Systema Naturae*.
[src:adnaviria/animal] In his original scheme, the animals were one of three kingdoms, divided into the classes of Vermes, Insecta, Pisces, Amphibia, Aves, and Mammalia.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Since then, the last four have all been subsumed into a single phylum, the Chordata, while his Insecta (which included the crustaceans and arachnids) and Vermes have been renamed or broken up.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The process was begun in 1793 by Jean-Baptiste de Lamarck, who called the Vermes *une espèce de chaos* ('a chaotic mess') and split the group into three new phyla: worms, echinoderms, and polyps (which contained corals and jellyfish).
[src:adnaviria/animal] By 1809, in his *Philosophie Zoologique*, Lamarck had created nine phyla apart from vertebrates (where he still had four phyla: mammals, birds, reptiles, and fish) and molluscs, namely cirripedes, annelids, crustaceans, arachnids, insects, worms, radiates, polyps, and infusorians.
[src:adnaviria/animal] This division into four was followed by the embryologist Karl Ernst von Baer in 1828, the zoologist Louis Agassiz in 1857, and the comparative anatomist Richard Owen in 1860.
[src:adnaviria/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into two subkingdoms: Metazoa (multicellular animals, with five phyla: coelenterates, echinoderms, articulates, molluscs, and vertebrates) and Protozoa (single-celled animals), including a sixth animal phylum, sponges.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The protozoa were later moved to the former kingdom Protista, leaving only the Metazoa as a synonym of Animalia.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The human population exploits a large number of other animal species for food, both of domesticated livestock species in animal husbandry and, mainly at sea, by hunting wild species.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Marine fish of many species are caught commercially for food.
[src:adnaviria/animal] A smaller number of species are farmed commercially.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Humans and their livestock make up more than 90% of the biomass of all terrestrial vertebrates, and almost as much as all insects combined.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Invertebrates including cephalopods, crustaceans, insects—principally bees and silkworms—and bivalve or gastropod molluscs are hunted or farmed for food, fibres.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Chickens, cattle, sheep, pigs, and other animals are raised as livestock for meat across the world.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Animal fibres such as wool and silk are used to make textiles, while animal sinews have been used as lashings and bindings, and leather is widely used to make shoes and other items.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Animals have been hunted and farmed for their fur to make items such as coats and hats.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Dyestuffs including carmine (cochineal), shellac, and kermes have been made from the bodies of insects.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Working animals including cattle and horses have been used for work and transport from the first days of agriculture.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Animals such as the fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster* serve a major role in science as experimental models.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Animals have been used to create vaccines since their discovery in the 18th century.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Some medicines such as the cancer drug trabectedin are based on toxins or other molecules of animal origin.
[src:adnaviria/animal] People have used hunting dogs to help chase down and retrieve animals, and birds of prey to catch birds and mammals, while tethered cormorants have been used to catch fish.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Poison dart frogs have been used to poison the tips of blowpipe darts.
[src:adnaviria/animal] A wide variety of animals are kept as pets, from invertebrates such as tarantulas, octopuses, and praying mantises, reptiles such as snakes and chameleons, and birds including canaries, parakeets, and parrots all finding a place.
[src:adnaviria/animal] However, the most kept pet species are mammals, namely dogs, cats, and rabbits.
[src:adnaviria/animal] There is a tension between the role of animals as companions to humans, and their existence as individuals with rights of their own.
[src:adnaviria/animal] A wide variety of terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sport.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The signs of the Western and Chinese zodiacs are based on animals.
[src:adnaviria/animal] In China and Japan, the butterfly has been seen as the personification of a person's soul, and in classical representation the butterfly is also the symbol of the soul.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Animals have been the subjects of art from the earliest times, both historical, as in ancient Egypt, and prehistoric, as in the cave paintings at Lascaux.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Major animal paintings include Albrecht Dürer's 1515 *The Rhinoceros*, and George Stubbs's c.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Insects, birds and mammals play roles in literature and film, such as in giant bug movies.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Animals including insects and mammals feature in mythology and religion.
[src:adnaviria/animal] The scarab beetle was sacred in ancient Egypt, and the cow is sacred in Hinduism.
[src:adnaviria/animal] Among other mammals, deer, horses, lions, bats, bears, and wolves are the subjects of myths and worship.
